In this class, We will use $\chi^2$ statistic as a hypotheisis testing model and parameters fitting to find the best-fit model.

$$\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N \left( \frac{x_i - \mu_i}{\sigma_i} \right)^2$$

Hypothesis testing using $\chi^2$¶

$\chi^2$ probability distribution:

$$P(\chi^2) \propto \left( \chi^2 \right)^{\frac{\nu}{2}-1} e^{-\chi^2/2}. $$

Where $\nu$ is the number of degrees of freedom.

p-value¶

  • If the p-value is not low, the data are consistent with the model, which is “ruled in”.
  • If the p-value is low, the model is “ruled out”

To use $\chi^2$ as a hypothesis test, we compute $\chi^2$ for a given dataset and model. We then ask the question: if the model is correct, what is the probability that this value of $\chi^2$, or a larger one, could arise by chance? This probability is called the $p$-value and may be calculated from $P(\chi^2)$ by integrating the area under the curve at values greater than some value of $\chi^2$.

In [43]:
nu = 50 # number of degrees of freedom
chisq1 = 30   # 1st value of chi-squared to test
chisq2 = 75 # 2nd value of chi-squared to test

# Range of values for chi-squared
xmin,xmax,nx = 10,90.,500   # change the nx to have a better resolution.
x_chi = np.linspace(xmin,xmax,nx)
dx = (xmax-xmin)/nx  ; print('dx',dx)    # bin size
ymin,ymax = 0.,0.05

## Calculate p value
dof = nu                                # number of degrees of freedom (data points minus fitted parameters)
p_value1 = 1 - stats.chi2.sf(chisq1,dof) # probability of chi-squared to exceed the value we've found
                                         # 1 - : Becasue The p value is calculated from intergrating from are that greater than value of chi-square
p_value2 = stats.chi2.sf(chisq2,dof)
print('p-value1 =', p_value1)
print('p-value2 =', p_value2)

# Determine chi-squared probability distribution
y_chi = stats.chi2.pdf(x_chi,nu)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10) )
plt.plot(x_chi,y_chi,color='black')


# Find 1st chi-squared test value in array, and shade area under the curve at greater values
plt.plot([chisq1,chisq1],[ymin,ymax],color='red',linestyle='dashed')
i = int((chisq1-xmin)/dx) ;print('i',i)
plt.fill_between(x_chi[:i], np.zeros_like(x_chi[:i]), y_chi[:i], color='red',alpha=0.5)
# The parameters are actualy x, y1, y2, Here:
# x is the a axis values. 
# y1 = 0 is a zero values for all x axis
# y2 = y_chi values


# Find 2nd chi-squared test value in array, and shade area under the curve at greater values
plt.plot([chisq2, chisq2],[ymin,ymax],color='blue',linestyle='dashed')

i = int((chisq2-xmin)/dx) ; print('i',i)
plt.fill_between(x_chi[i:], np.zeros_like(x_chi[i:]), y_chi[i:], color='blue', alpha=0.8)


# Complete plot
plt.xlabel(r'$\chi^2$')
plt.ylabel(r'$P(\chi^2)$')
plt.xlim(xmin,xmax)
plt.ylim(ymin,ymax)

plt.savefig('ChiSquare_two_tail.png',dpi=300)

y = b¶

Could these points be fit by a constant $y = b$, and if so what is the best-fitting value of $b$? We can answer that question by minimizing the $\chi^2$ statistic:

In [8]:
from scipy.optimize import curve_fit

def f_cst(x, B): # this is your 'straight line' y=B
    y=B
    return y

popt_cst, pcov_cst = curve_fit(f_cst, x, y)        # your data x, y to fit

In [12]:
# Function which evaluates the chi-squared value of a model y=b for the (x,y) dataset
def chisqstraightline1(p,x,y,yerr):
  b = p[0]
  return np.sum( ((y - b)/yerr)**2 )  ## (data - model)/sigma_error


# Find the best-fitting model y=b to the (x,y) dataset by minimising chi-squared
from scipy.optimize import minimize


p0 = [1.] # initial guess of the value of b (result should not depend on this)
result1 = minimize(chisqstraightline1,p0,args=(x,y,yerr)) # perform the minimisation

b1 = result1['x'][0] # best-fitting value of b

minchisq1 = result1['fun'] # chi-squared value corresponding to the best fit
dof1 = n-1 # number of degrees of freedom (data points minus fitted parameters)

print('Best-fitting value of b =', b1)
print('Minimum chi-squared =', minchisq1)
print('Number of degrees of freedom =', dof1)

Best-fitting value of b = 1.7899999897904915
Minimum chi-squared = 31.635200000000005
Number of degrees of freedom = 9

# Function which evaluates the chi-squared value of a model y=a*x+b for the (x,y) dataset
def chisqstraightline2(p,x,y,yerr):
  a = p[0]
  return np.sum(  ( (y - a*x ) /yerr)**2 )    ## (data - model)/sigma_error


# Find the best fitting model y=a*x to the (x,y) dataset by minimising chi-squared
p0 = [0.2] # initial guess of the values of a (result should not depend on this)

result2 = minimize(chisqstraightline2,p0,args=(x,y,yerr)) # perform the minimisation
a2 = result2['x'] # best-fitting values of a

minchisq2 = result2['fun']          # chi-squared value corresponding to the best fit
dof2 = n-1                        # number of degrees of freedom (data points minus fitted parameters)
p2 = stats.chi2.sf(minchisq2,dof2) # probability of chi-squared to exceed the value we've found

print('Best-fitting value of a =', a2)
print(r'Minimum chi-squared $\chi^2$ =', minchisq2)
print('Number of degrees of freedom =', dof2)
print('p-value =', p2)

y=a*x + b¶

This situation is hence very unlikely, suggesting that the model is not a good fit to the data.

Instead, could these points be fit by a straight line $y = ax + b$? Minimize $\chi^2$ as before:

In [21]:

    return a*x + b

popt, pcov = curve_fit(f_linear, x, y)   # your data x, y to fit

# Function which evaluates the chi-squared value of a model y=a*x+b for the (x,y) dataset
def chisqstraightline3(p,x,y,yerr):
  a,b = p[0],p[1]
  return np.sum( ( (y - (a*x + b) )/yerr)**2 )    ## (data - model)/sigma_error


# Find the best fitting model y=a*x+b to the (x,y) dataset by minimising chi-squared
p0 = [0.2, 1.] # initial guess of the values of a,b (result should not depend on this)

result = minimize(chisqstraightline3,p0,args=(x,y,yerr)) # perform the minimisation
a3, b3 = result['x'] # best-fitting values of a,b

minchisq3 = result['fun']          # chi-squared value corresponding to the best fit
dof3 = n-2                         # number of degrees of freedom (data points minus fitted parameters)
p3 = stats.chi2.sf(minchisq3,dof3) # probability of chi-squared to exceed the value we've found

print('Best-fitting value of a =', a3)
print('Best-fitting value of b =', b3)
print(r'Minimum chi-squared $\chi^2$ =', minchisq3)
print('Number of degrees of freedom =', dof3)
print('p-value =', p3)

Join confident region¶

We know that today, the dark energy is domonated in our Universe compare to matter. The result is tested by many observational data of experiments.

(Planck result)

Example: The join analytical measurements of galaxy clusters, supernovae, and Cosmic microwaves background (CMB) to estimate the dark matter parameter ($\Omega_{m} \approx 0.3$), and the dark energy ($\Omega_{\Lambda} \approx 0.7$) in the universe.

A model typically contains free parameters. How do we determine the most likely values of these parameters and their error ranges?

  • Assuming that we are fitting a model with 2 free parameters (a,b).

  • The “best-fitting” values of (a,b) are found by minimizing the $\chi^2$ statistic.

  • The joint error distribution of parameters (a,b) can be found by calculating the values of $\chi^2$ over a grid of (a,b) and enclosing a particular region $\chi^2 < \chi^2_{min} + \Delta \chi^2$

  • Plot contour 2D $\chi^2 < \chi^2_{min} + \Delta \chi^2$

In [31]:
# Function which evaluates the chi-squared value of a model y=a*x+b for the (x,y) dataset
def chisqstraightline4(p,x,y,yerr):
  a,b = p[0],p[1]
  return np.sum( ( (y - (a*x + b) )/yerr)**2 )    ## (data - model)/sigma_error
In [52]:
from matplotlib import cm

# Use the chi-squared method to create joint confidence intervals 
# of model parameters a,b fit to a dataset
# Create grid of values of the model parameters a,b

amin,amax,na = 0., 0.5, 200
bmin,bmax,nb = -1., 2., 200

da,db = (amax-amin)/na,(bmax-bmin)/nb

alst = np.linspace(amin+0.5*da,amax-0.5*da,na)  ## shift  1 step 0.5*da
blst = np.linspace(bmin+0.5*db,bmax-0.5*db,nb)
#print('alst', alst, '\n blst',blst)

# Evaluate the chi-squared value at each grid point 
# (i.e. for each set of model parameters)
# (Note that we are not performing a *minimisation* 
# for each set of model parameters, just an evaluation)


chisq4 = np.empty((na,nb))
for i in range(na):
  for j in range(nb):
    p0 = [alst[i],blst[j]]
    chisq4[i,j] = chisqstraightline4(p0,x,y,yerr)

    
# Find the minimum value of chi-squared across the grid
minchisq4 = np.amin(chisq4)
print('Minimum chi-squared =',minchisq4)


# Find the values of the model parameters at the point of minimum chi-squared
i,j = np.unravel_index( chisq4.argmin(), chisq4.shape )
a2,b2 = alst[i],blst[j]
print('Best-fitting value of a =',a2)
print('Best-fitting value of b =',b2)


# These values of delta chi-squared correspond to the 1-sigma, 2-sigma and 3-sigma confidence regions
clst = np.array([0.,2.30,6.17,11.8])   # Source: Numerical Recipes, chapter 15.
  
# Add the minimum chi-squared to these intervals to obtain the chi-squared contours for the plot
clst += minchisq4
print('confident region',clst)


# Make a contour plot of these chi-squared values
alst2,blst2 = np.meshgrid(alst,blst,indexing='ij')


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
ax.contour(alst2, blst2, chisq4, levels=clst, linewidths=2.5)   #,cmap='rainbow' ) #,colors='k')
ax.contourf(alst2, blst2, chisq4, levels=clst,cmap='rainbow') #,colors='k')


# Indicate the best-fitting model parameters
ax.plot([a2],[b2],marker='o',markersize=15,color='red',linestyle='None')

ax.set_xlabel(r'$a$')
ax.set_ylabel(r'$b$')
#ax.set_title('Join confident',fontsize=28,y=1.02)
plt.grid(ls='--', alpha=0.3)

plt.savefig('Straight_line_chisquare_confident_region.png',dpi=300)

Advanced Activity (option)¶

You probably need a cosmology course, to understand the LambdaCDM model.

We will use a recent supernova distance-redshift dataset to estimate the cosmological parameters $(\Omega_m,\Omega_\Lambda)$. Firstly read the data using astropy to compute a fiducial model.

Then:

  • Minimize $\chi^2$ to find the best-fitting parameters of $(\Omega_m, \Omega_\Lambda)$.
  • Make a 2D confidence regions for 2 parameters $(\Omega_m, \Omega_\Lambda)$
  • (optional) Determine the individual errors in $\Omega_m$ and $\Omega_\Lambda$

  • For the LambdaCDM model, you can have look at the paper: https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-6596/354/1/012005/pdf

  • For the supernovae and cosmological parameters: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1811.02374.pdf

from astropy.cosmology import LambdaCDM

# Function which determines the supernova luminosity distance for given cosmological parameters (Omega_m, Omega_L)
def get_darkmatter_model(Omega_m, Omega_L, z):  # initial data point: (Omega_m, Omega_L), redshift: z
    #om,ol = p[0],p[1]
    
    cosmo = LambdaCDM(H0=70.,Om0=Omega_m,Ode0=Omega_L) 
    # Hubble constant = 70, Om0 dark matter, Ode0
    
    print('Lambda CDM model parameters :',cosmo)
    
    r = cosmo.comoving_distance(z).value
    print('comiving distance value',r)
    
    dl = r*(1.+z)    ## distance 

    return 5.*np.log10(dl) + 25.   # equation (6) in the paper.

LambdaCDM?

Init signature:
LambdaCDM(
    H0,
    Om0,
    Ode0,
    Tcmb0=0,
    Neff=3.04,
    m_nu=<Quantity 0. eV>,
    Ob0=None,
    name=None,
)
Docstring:     
FLRW cosmology with a cosmological constant and curvature.

This has no additional attributes beyond those of FLRW.

Parameters
----------

H0 : float or `~astropy.units.Quantity`
    Hubble constant at z = 0.  If a float, must be in [km/sec/Mpc]

Om0 : float
    Omega matter: density of non-relativistic matter in units of the
    critical density at z=0.

Ode0 : float
    Omega dark energy: density of the cosmological constant in units of
    the critical density at z=0.

Tcmb0 : float or scalar `~astropy.units.Quantity`, optional
    Temperature of the CMB z=0. If a float, must be in [K].
    Default: 0 [K]. Setting this to zero will turn off both photons
    and neutrinos (even massive ones).

Neff : float, optional
    Effective number of Neutrino species. Default 3.04.

m_nu : `~astropy.units.Quantity`, optional
    Mass of each neutrino species. If this is a scalar Quantity, then all
    neutrino species are assumed to have that mass. Otherwise, the mass of
    each species. The actual number of neutrino species (and hence the
    number of elements of m_nu if it is not scalar) must be the floor of
    Neff. Typically this means you should provide three neutrino masses
    unless you are considering something like a sterile neutrino.

Ob0 : float or None, optional
    Omega baryons: density of baryonic matter in units of the critical
    density at z=0.  If this is set to None (the default), any
    computation that requires its value will raise an exception.

name : str, optional
    Name for this cosmological object.

Examples
--------
>>> from astropy.cosmology import LambdaCDM
>>> cosmo = LambdaCDM(H0=70, Om0=0.3, Ode0=0.7)

The comoving distance in Mpc at redshift z:

>>> z = 0.5
>>> dc = cosmo.comoving_distance(z)
